{{About|the telephone number|the year|711|the number|711 (number)|the convenience store chain|7-Eleven}}
[[File:MUTCD D9-21.svg|right|125px]]
In [[Canada]] and the [[United States]], the '''711''' [[telephone number]] is used for the [[Telecommunications Relay Service]] to [[translate]] from [[Telecommunications devices for the deaf|TDD]] for the [[deaf]] to [[Speech communication|speech]], and vice versa.  The [[relay]] service allows [[deaf]] people to converse with the [[hearing (person)|hearing]] over the phone through an [[operator (profession)|operator]].  711 is one of eight [[N11 code]]s for [[abbreviated dialing]] in the [[North American Numbering Plan]].

==Requirement==
In the U.S., every [[phone company]] is required to connect persons who dial 711 to a TRS [[call center]] from a working number.<ref>{{cite web |title=FCC MANDATES NATIONWIDE IMPLEMENTATION OF 711 ACCESS TO TELECOMMUNICATIONS RELAY SERVICES (TRS) |url=http://transition.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Common_Carrier/News_Releases/2000/nrcc0038.html |publisher=U.S. [[Federal Communications Commission]] |date=July 21, 2000 |accessdate=May 1, 2012 }}</ref>

In July 2007, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] ruled that the 711 requirement extended to [[VOIP]] [[telephony]].<ref>{{cite web |title=DISABILITY ACCESS REQUIREMENTS EXTENDED TO VOIP SERVICES |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DOC-273452A1.pdf |format=PDF  |publisher=U.S. [[Federal Communications Commission]] |date=May 31, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2012 }}</ref>

