{{BLP primary sources|date=July 2011}} {{Infobox person | name = Emily Schulman | image = | alt = | caption =Emily Schulman on '''Small Wonder''' | birth_name = Emily Hope Schulman | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|08|17}} | birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], USA | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Actress | years_active = 1985&nbsp;– 1995 | website = }}
'''Emily Hope Schulman''' (born August 17, 1977) is a former [[child actress]] and commercial agent, and current acting instructor. She is best known for her role as next-door neighbor Harriet Brindle on the sitcom ''[[Small Wonder (TV series)|Small Wonder]]'', which ran from [[1985 in television|1985]] to [[1989 in television|1989]].
==Career== By age six, Schulman appeared in over 200 TV commercials.<ref name=acting>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivanhope.com/acting|title=Ivanhope Acting Consultations|publisher=Ivanhope.com|accessdate=May 13, 2018}}</ref> In 1984, she was then cast in the role of Harriet on the pilot for ''Small Wonder'', which ran for four seasons and 96 episodes. Schulman's childhood work, though often later lampooned for its perceived kitsch, received recognition by her contemporaries: she twice won [[Young Artist Awards]] and was nominated for the peer honor three other times. Additional television credits include ''[[Finders Keepers (American game show)|Finders Keepers]]'', ''[[Hotel (U.S. TV series)|Hotel]]'', ''[[Mr. Belvedere]]'', ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' and ''[[The Wonder Years]]''.
Schulman also starred in the [[1989 in film|1989]] films ''[[Troop Beverly Hills]]'' and ''[[Caddie Woodlawn]]''. Her last acting appearance was on the television series ''[[Christy (TV series)|Christy]]'' (with her ''[[Troop Beverly Hills]]'' co-star [[Kellie Martin]]), in which she played Ruby Mae Morrison.
==Post-acting career== At 17, Schulman began a career shift away from the cameras. In 2008, after 13 years as the head of Acme Talent & Literary's Commercial Division, Schulman relocated her department to its current home at Talentworks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117996871?refCatId=18|title=TalentWorks snaps up Acme|publisher=Variety|date=2008-12-04|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref> Schulman teaches acting in Connecticut.<ref name=acting/>
==Family== Schulman married Derek Webster in 2002; the couple have four children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivanhope.com/family|title=The Webster Family|publisher=Ivanhope.com|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>
